{
  "doc_id": "22771",
  "text": "High concentrations of diverse free radicals and oxidants generate potent reactive oxygen species (ROS) that can damage cell DNA by direct oxidation or by interfering with the mechanisms of DNA repair. ROS may also react with proteins and lipids, forming derivative products that may alter intracellular homeostasis favoring the accumulation of mutations that, in turn, contribute to the multistage carcinogenesis process [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] .",
